g.text: Everyone at Yurgosky is one of three things: (1) Engineer, (2) Business Analyst, and (3) Project Manager. The people working on every project think about how to streamline processes, build better technology and provide an incredible experience to clients. Because of this structure, we do more “workshops” than meetings, more “prototyping” than design documentation, and more “innovation” than “specing”.

We define an organization’s operating model and align the organization with the right tools to improve their business processes. We are extremely transparent in how we work, integrating training to build internal capacity while we build.
Analytics are embedded into everything we do. We define compelling metrics that drive adoption and impact, allowing people at every level of an organization to save time and be more effective.

We use the right type of project management for each project, and we specialize in Agile. Using Agile project management, we create products through rapid prototyping and iterations that get features into users’ hands quickly and allow them to provide constructive feedback that can be used to enhance the next iteration.

Agile project management is appropriate when the goals are clear, but the ways of achieving them are not yet concrete. This flexible project management style builds products iteratively with feedback from different levels of the organization over the life of the project.

During the proposal stage, a significant amount of time is spent carefully scoping and allocating hours against detailed project deliverables to ensure expectations are closely aligned from the onset. Contingencies are factored in and provisions for possible future changes are included. Understanding goals and key deliverables reduces time spent correcting and managing changes once the project has been kicked-off.

Once the project is active, the budget is tracked and reconciled on a continual basis, along with a weekly analysis and summary report. Potential risks are assessed, along with recommendations for corrective action. If changes to the scope of work and/or timeline are necessary, stakeholders are notified and change requests will be drafted for approval.
Upon project completion, budget vs actuals are evaluated, providing insight to benefit future projects.

The type of feedback and the audience is important at each iteration. As the product becomes more concrete, there is less risk associated with rejection, lowering the opportunity cost of changes. Because of this, initial feedback from senior staff about the trajectory of the project is very important.

Yurgosky uses GoodData as its business intelligence tool for forecasting and deeper analytics on a project-by-project basis. We also use Apple Computers and G Suite applications for internal business collaboration and email and MS Office Suite for spreadsheets.

Yurgosky was born out of a desire to provide better analytics, products, and services to non-profits. To do this, we have established a model that has dramatically outperformed the industry-standard success rates. Our model is based on three tenets: strategy, analytics, and project management.
